The paper discusses coordination languages, which are used to specify composite software applications using components that are only available separately or later in time. This topic falls under the software engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The paper also discusses the distinction between coordination languages and general programming languages, which falls under the programming languages (cs.PL) sub-category. The paper also touches on distributed computing (cs.DC) and system design (cs.SY) as it discusses the use of external interfaces to coordinate components. Finally, the paper discusses the trade-offs of academic attention, which could fall under the digital libraries (cs.DL) sub-category.
